Python coding by Gracieli Scremin¶

Project Description¶

Objective - Preliminary Data Analysis. Explore the dataset and practice extracting basic observations about the data. The idea is for you to get comfortable working in Python.

You are expected to do the following :

  1. Come up with a customer profile (characteristics of a customer) of the different products
  2. Perform uni-variate and multi-variate analyses
  3. Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the company in targeting new customers

Context - The data is for customers of the treadmill product(s) of a retail store called Cardio Good Fitness. It contains the following variables

  • Product - the model no. of the treadmill
  • Age - in no of years, of the customer
  • Gender - of the customer
  • Education - in no. of years, of the customer
  • Marital Status - of the customer
  • Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  • Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  • Income - of the customer
  • Miles- expected to run

Explore the dataset to identify differences between customers of each product. You can also explore relationships between the different attributes of customers. You can approach it from any other line of questioning that you feel could be relevant for the business.

Minimum Steps for exploration:¶

  • Importing the dataset into Python & understanding the structure of the dataset
  • Basic summary of data and graphical exploration
  • Observations from the dataset

Best Practices for Notebook :¶

The notebook should be well-documented, with inline comments explaining the functionality of code and markdown cells containing comments on the observations and insights. The notebook should be run from start to finish in a sequential manner before submission. It is preferable to remove all warnings and errors before submission. The notebook should be submitted as an HTML file (.html) and NOT as a notebook file (.ipynb)

Best Practices for Presentation :¶

The presentation should be made keeping in mind that the audience will be a business leader like CMO, COO, CFO, or CEO. The key points in the presentation should be the following business overview of the problem and solution approach key findings and insights which can drive business decisions model overview and performance summary business recommendations Focus on explaining the takeaways in an easy-to-understand manner. Inclusion of the potential benefits of implementing the solution will give you the edge. Copying and pasting from the notebook is not a good idea, and it is better to avoid showing codes unless they are the focal point of your presentation. The presentation should be submitted as a PDF file (.pdf) and NOT as a .pptx file. A presentation template has been provided for reference.

Submission Guidelines :¶

There are two parts to the submission: A well commented Jupyter notebook [format - .html] A presentation as you would present to the top management/business leaders [format - .pdf] Any assignment found copied/ plagiarized with other groups will not be graded and awarded zero marks Please ensure timely submission as any submission post-deadline will not be accepted for evaluation Submission will not be evaluated if, it is submitted post-deadline, or, more than 2 files are submitted Happy Learning!!

# The minimum number of years of Education for this dataset is 12 
# so we begin the classification into different educational categories 
# with that number.
conditions_educ = [(df.Education == 12),
             (df.Education > 12) & (df.Education <= 15),
             (df.Education == 16),
             (df.Education > 16)]
In [440]:
values_educ = ['High_School', 'Some_college', 'College', 'Graduate_School']
In [441]:
df['Education_Level'] = np.select(conditions_educ, values_educ)
In [442]:
df['Education_Level'] = df.Education_Level.astype('category')

#Function to calculate IQR
def IQR(feature):
    return feature.quantile(0.75) - feature.quantile(0.25)

  • Miles expected to run vary widely, from a minimum of 21 miles to a max of 360 miles (presumably per week). The mean is greater than the median value indicating a right-skewed distribution.

Exploring numerical variables through Univariate Analysis¶

# Function below helps to create a boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable. It takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.

def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='green') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins) if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='g', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

Visually exploring categorical variables¶

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
def bar_perc(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: 1-d categorical feature array
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage

Plot bivariate charts between variables to understand their interaction with each other.

Correlation

In [81]:
# Check for correlation among numerical variables
num_var = ['Age','Usage','Fitness','Income','Miles']

corr = df[num_var].corr()

# plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(16,12))
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True,cmap='coolwarm',
        fmt=".2f",
        xticklabels=corr.columns,
        yticklabels=corr.columns);
In [82]:
sns.pairplot(df[num_var], corner=True)
plt.show()

Observations

  • As one would expect, data shows positive correlation between Miles (expected miles run per week) and Usage (average number of times per week customer wants to use treadmill), 0.76
  • We also observe a positive correlation (0.79) between expected miles run per week and self-rated fitness level
  • Age and Fitness, Age and Miles, and Age and Usage are not observed to be strongly correlated
  • Moderate positive correlations observed between Income and Usage, Income and Fitness, and Income and Miles
  • Important to note that none of the relationships described above imply causality

Conclusion¶

We have synthesized key findings below into customer profiles for each of the three treadmills sold at Cardio Good Fitness: TM195, TM498, and TM798

Customer Profiles¶

TM195

  • The typical TM195 customer is in their mid 20s to mid 30s, more likely to be in a relationship than single, college-educated and with an yearly income of about $46,000

  • The typical user is also moderately fit and expects to use the treadmill 3 to 4 days a week to run about 80 miles

TM498

  • The typical TM498 customer is in their mid 20s to mid 40s, more likely to be in a relationship than single, college-educated and with an yearly income of about $49,000

  • The typical user is also moderately fit and expects to use the treadmill on average 3 days a week to run about 87 miles

TM798

  • The typical TM798 customer is male, in their mid 20s to mid 30s, more likely to be in a relationship than single, more likely to have a graduate degree and with an yearly income of about $75,000

  • The typical user is also very fit and expects heavy use out of the treadmill: 4 to 5 days a week to run about 167 miles

Recommendations based on analysis insights¶

  • Based on our findings, it seems that a more differentiated branding strategy is needed for the TM195 and TM498 treadmill models as currently we observe much overlap between these customer groups
  • For the TM195 model we recommend targeting customers who are recent college grads/young professionals with yearly income in the $40,000 to $50,000 range (therefore more price-sensitive) and interested in maintaining or incorporating moderate to high levels of weekly exercise
  • TM498 seems to attract a customer base that is slightly older than TM195 and TM798 customers. A recommendation for this treadmill model would be to target individuals in their late 30s to mid 40s with yearly income around $50,000 to $60,000 who desire to keep or incorporate moderate levels of weekly exercise in their lives
  • TM798 customers are established young professionals, high income-earning, highly motivated runners. They seem to follow the mantra work hard, play hard. We recommend a branding strategy that plays to these customer characteristics in order to continue to resonate with them and expand the brands reach among this target audience
